<TEXT>
blueprints for abolishing most tariffs and 
many other barriers to trade with canada are headed for a senate 
vote this week after winning a strong endorsement in the house 
this is the crowning achievement of this president and this 
administration on the trade front rep philip m crane rill 
said as the house voted 36640 to approve the pact signed in 
january by president reagan and canadian prime minister brian 
mulroney 
the bill would authorize the president to phase out most tariffs 
on canadian imports over the next decade it also envisions ending 
an array of other trade restrictions 
the senate is expected to act on the measure this week and send 
it to reagans desk it won approval tuesday from the senate 
finance committee 
but canadian counterpart legislation is stalled in that nations 
appointive senate where it is running into liberal party 
opposition 
lawmakers here are saying the agreement is needed in part as a 
balance to rising protectionism within the european economic 
community 
many europeans are talking about free trade as being something 
for europeans within that bloc i hope they dont go that way 
said democratic vice presidential candidate lloyd bentsen dtexas 
the chairman of the senate finance committee 
the agreement would not set up a common market between the 
united states and canada that would mean adopting the same set of 
tariffs for products produced in third countries 
the freetrade agreement allows the united states and canada to 
maintain their own set of thirdcountry tariffs while dropping most 
tariffs on the annual 166 billion in goods and services traded 
across their common border 
the united states already has a freetrade agreement with israel 
tariffs currently apply to about 25 percent of uscanada trade 
advocates claim the pact will result in increased us exports 
and resulting jobs while lowering consumer prices but some 
industries are complaining that they are likely to get hurt 
the blueprint immediately would drop 10 percent of existing 
tariffs applying to goods ranging from telecommunications gear to 
whiskey and rum the rest would be phased out over 10 years 
under the pact it would become easier for americans to invest 
in canada and canadians to invest in this country barriers to a 
wide array of exports of services would be swept away but 
transportation and cultural services would be exempted 
the agreement would eliminate barriers to import and export of 
crude oil petroleum products natural gas coal electricity 
uranium and other nuclear fuels 
tariffs on autos and auto parts which account for a third of 
trade between the two countries would be eliminated ninetyfive 
percent of such trade between the two countries already moves 
without tariffs 
to get the dutyfree treatment however autos and auto parts 
would have to be 50 percent manufactured in north america the 
provision is aimed at japanese and korean auto assembly plants in 
canada 
autostate lawmakers for the most part supported the measure 
based on a promise that us trade officials would try to negotiate 
a provision under which dutyfree treatment would be restricted to 
automotive products with a minimum of 60 percent north american 
content 
rep byron dorgan dnd said the agreement would leave us 
with canadian agricultural markets that are largely closed to 
american agricultural producers and american markets that are 
largely open to canadian agricultural producers and im concerned 
about that 
a chief problem he said have been canadian rail subsidies for 
grain shipped throught that countrys big port at thunder bay ont 
american producers receive nothing comparable and thus are at a 
disadvantage he said 
under the pact the canadians agreed to end rail subsidies for 
grain shipped through their west coast port of vancouver 
rep hal daub rneb said he was confident that the measure 
would protect not only wheat but corn sugar and dry edible beans 
from a wave of canadian imports 
he also said the agreement would raise the prospects of success 
in the current uruguay round of trade talks and thus end the 
subsidy shootout in which the only winners are the giddy greedy 
buyers happily snatching up agricultural commodities at prices 
below the cost of production 
</TEXT>
