<TEXT>
nasa began the final countdown 
tuesday for firing the space shuttle discoverys huge main engines 
a hotfire test that must be passed before the craft can make its 
longdelayed return to space 
the 22second firing of discoverys three engines was set for 
730 am edt wednesday weather conditions appeared favorable 
kennedy space centers countdown clocks frozen at the 11hour 
mark after a similar test was scrubbed last week began ticking at 
610 pm as scheduled the countdown included three hold 
periods totaling two hours and 20 minutes for any timeconsuming 
tasks that might crop up 
at 1150 pm the launch team began pumping 385000 gallons of 
liquid hydrogen and 143000 gallons of liquid oxygen propellant 
into discoverys 154foottall external fuel tank 
engineers made a late computer change to avoid a possible 
recurrence of last weeks test shutdown when an electronic sensor 
erroneously indicated that a valve was not closing properly on the 
no 2 engine 
although the offending unit was replaced engineers worried that 
a valve sensor on the no 3 engine might also be error prone and 
repeat the scrub rather than replace the position indicator they 
changed computer instructions to allow more leeway in the report of 
the valves position 
the engines were expected to develop 11 million pounds of 
thrust but use only a fraction of the fuel 
discovery was fastened to its launch pad by eight bolts each 
three feet long and three inches in diameter during the test each 
engine was to fire on a staggered schedule that totals 22 seconds 
the two solid fuel booster rockets that flank the shuttle tank were 
not to be ignited 
the test has been delayed five times because of problems with 
ground equipment and thursday because an electronic sensor 
mistakenly reported a closed valve as open 
the national aeronautics and space administration said it will 
announce a launch date for discovery after the engines and ship are 
certified for flight the date has slipped from july last year to 
february then june then midaugust then late september it 
appears now to be possible no earlier than october 
when discovery finally flies with a fiveman crew it will end 
a 2year nearhiatus in american space activity that began with 
the explosion of the space shuttle challenger on jan 28 1986 
nasa normally performs shuttle flight readiness tests only on 
new ships but it is requiring them for discovery which has flown 
six times because of the many modifications on both ship and 
engines and because of the length of time since the last mission 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

