<TEXT>
a divided appeals panel granted yonkers a 
temporary reprieve from bankrupting fines hours after a state board 
took control of the citys finances in a dispute over housing 
desegregation 
i knew we could find sanity outside judge leonard sands 
courtroom said city council minority leader nicholas longo who 
was found in contempt by the us district judge for refusing to 
endorse sands housing desegregation plan 
three other councilmen and the city also were declared in 
contempt and subjected to fines since the aug 2 council vote that 
defied the desegregation order 
the oneweek stay granted tuesday by the 2nd us circuit court 
of appeals staved off layoffs due to the citys 100aday fine 
which has been doubled daily city officials had predicted layoffs 
would begin as early as next tuesday 
for longo and the three other councilmen the stay halted their 
500aday personal fines which did not double and removed sands 
threat of imprisonment he made had their contempt continued through 
today 
the appellate panel split 21 on whether to grant the request to 
stay the fines the majority decision said the city and council 
members barely satisfied the standards for a stay pending 
appeal the judges set arguments before the full appeals panel 
for aug 17 
earlier the yonkers emergency financial control board created 
in 1984 when the state bailed out yonkers from imminent bankruptcy 
agreed to assume the fiscal powers of the city council and raised 
the spectre of criminal charges against the defiant councilmen 
in short our goal is to save yonkers from itself said new 
york secretary of state gail shaffer who heads the emergency board 
the board has sweeping powers to control spending in new yorks 
fourthlargest city but it cannot enact the zoning changes that 
would allow sands housing plan to go forward 
the board voted 51 to impose a wage and hiring freeze and made 
council members subject to misdemeanor charges if they refuse to 
abide by board rules those rules forbid city officials from 
incurring debts the city cannot pay the target of the vote is the 
four council members who voted against the desegregation resolution 
in 1985 sand found the city liable for intentionally 
segregating its schools and housing over a 40year period the 
council reached a settlement with the judge in january but a 
public uproar followed and officials recanted 
last week the council voted 43 against a resolution endorsing 
construction of 800 units of middleincome housing throughout the 
city of 194000 people by private developers the judge 
specifically asked them to endorse it and the measure also 
contained zoning changes and a package of financial incentives 
mayor nicholas wasicsko who canceled a lastditch council 
meeting he had called for tonight after the stay was granted said 
he did not think the emergency boards actions would have the 
desired effect the only thing that will make any difference is 
the threat of removal of the dissident council members from 
office he said 
only gov mario cuomo can remove an elected official and he has 
said he does not want to get involved until the legal process is 
completed 
lawyers for the defiant councilmen argued that sand exceeded his 
authority by ordering the city council to pass legislation for the 
housing plan 
there are limits to a federal courts authority even to remedy 
an unconstitutional action said james d harmon attorney for 
councilman peter chema 
but michael sussman attorney for the national assocation for 
the advancement of colored people said the appeals court had a 
duty to uphold sand 
the dignity of the federal court is under assault said 
sussman by a group of citizens who think theyre above the law 
</TEXT>
