<TEXT>
cia director william h webster says the soviets 
are trying harder than ever to tap into us intelligence and that 
security breaches in the last three years have cost the united 
states billions of dollars 
in a speech tuesday to the american bar association he said he 
has set up a special counterintelligence agency to protect the 
cias foreign operations 
this center was badly needed too many things were falling 
between chairs he told the associations annual meeting about 
12000 lawyers are attending the weeklong convention which ends 
today 
over the past three years we have discovered more 
penetrations of the us defense and intelligence communities than 
at any time in our history said webster who took over the 
central intelligence agency in may 1987 after 10 years as director 
of the federal bureau of investigation 
the costs of these compromises are estimated in the billions 
of dollars he added 
the soviet intelligence services the kgb and gru represent 
by far the most significant intelligence threat despite soviet 
glasnost and perestroika weve actually seen an increase this year 
in soviet atempts to recruit us sources he said 
glasnost is the name of soviet leader mikhail s gorbachevs 
drive for greater discussion on selected subjects perestroika is 
his program to make soviet economy more efficient 
webster a former us court of appeals judge said the soviets 
were more aggressive and more sophisticated than ever in their 
search for information on us nuclear strategic forces foreign 
policy nato technology american intelligence sources and 
methods and congressional intentions 
he cited two cases this summer both involving canada the 
arrest of canadian stephen ratkai on charges of trying to pass us 
military secrets to the soviet union in newfoundland and the 
expulsion or barring from canada of 17 soviet officials for 
allegedly attempting to steal us military and commercial 
technology in montreal 
webster said the cia and fbi were working closely together in 
offensive and defensive measures to counter foreign spies 
he said the cia collected information on 253 terrorist threats 
around the world over the past 3 years and he cited one success 
and one failure when warnings were relayed into the field 
in one such case the agency received a report that terrorists 
planned to assassinate the senior american diplomat in a major 
eastern country when he arrived for a meeting he arranged for 
the meeting to be held elsewhere and escaped the attempt on his 
life 
sadly just a few days ago a similar warning was issued to 
another figure in south america the warning was not heeded and he 
was assassinated 
cia public affairs director william baker said the director 
intentionally did not name the two people involved and that the 
agency would not comment further 
webster said terrorism was again on the increase from 500 
incidents in 1981 to almost 800 in 1985 and a projected 900 this 
year 
about half of these terrorist incidents worldwide are directed 
against us persons and property he said 
however he credited fbi intelligencegathering with checking 
terrorist bombings and other attacks within the united states down 
from 100 a year to less than a dozen in the last two years 
