<TEXT>
a major earthquake shook the vicinity 
of the solomon islands in the south pacific today seismologists 
said there were no immediate reports of damage or injury 
the quake which registered 73 on the richter scale was 
centered 60 miles east of guadalcanal said the bureau of mineral 
resources 
the pacific tsunami warning center in honolulu reported no 
threat of a destructive pacificwide tsunami or tidal wave but 
said some areas could experience small sea level changes 
mineral resources spokesman trevor jones said the quake hit at 
238 pm 1238 am edt in tokyo japans central 
meteorological agency recorded the quake slightly later 
the solomons a double chain of six large islands and many 
smaller ones is 1000 miles east of port moresby papua new 
guinea and 1600 miles northeast of sydney australia 
the islands have a mainly melanesian population of about 
160000 the capital honiara was built near the famed guadalcanal 
battleground of world war ii and has about 20000 residents 
the richter scale measures the magnitude of a quake at its 
epicenter according to ground motion as recorded on seismographs 
an quake of 5 on the scale is considered very strong and a 6 
severe capable of widespread damage near the epicenter 
a 7 reading is a major earthquake capable of widespread 
heavy damage 
every increase of one digit represents a tenfold increase in 
magnitude thus a reading of 75 would be 10 times stronger than 
one of 65 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

