<TEXT>
the us navy is investigating 
allegations that a navy ship refused to rescue some vietnamese boat 
people who later resorted to murder and cannibalism to survive at 
sea officials said today 
navy officials said the sailors reported giving food and water 
to the boat people not considering them to be in dire straits 
weve made all information available to the united states and 
we know they are conducting an investigation and are very serious 
about it said robert cooper local representative of the un 
high commission on refugees cooper said in a telephone interview 
that the probe began last month 
he said the 52 refugees who survived the 37day ordeal charged 
that crewmen of the uss dubuque refused to take them aboard even 
though their boat was disabled and they were dying of exposure and 
starvation 
cooper said the refugees reported that 58 people died during the 
south china sea crossing which began may 22 when the group left 
the mekong delta town of ben tre aboard a 35foot wooden boat 
its engine failed two or three days later 
by the june 9 encounter with the dubuque according to the 
refugees there was one dead refugee aboard the motor was not 
working they were drifting for 19 days people had died of 
exposure hunger and thirst cooper said 
the refugees claimed to have later killed some of their 
companions and eaten their flesh to survive cooper said the 
great majority of other deaths also occurred after the 
encounter with the dubuque 
officials at subic bay naval base northwest of manila and at 
the us navys surface force pacific fleet office in san diego 
calif confirmed that an investigation was under way 
they said the dubuques commander reported that the refugee boat 
was seaworthy and that they left the vietnamese after giving them 
more than 400 pounds of food 50 gallons of water navigational 
charts and sailing directions 
a navy spokesman cmdr david dillon in san diego said he did 
not think the crew would have turned the refugees away if their 
boat was disabled 
the manila chronicle quoted some of the refugees as saying the 
crew told them the dubuque was on a dangerous mission and could 
not take them aboard 
dillon said the dubuque was headed for the persian gulf but 
that its destination would not have been an excuse not to rescue 
the vietnamese if their boat was in distress 
its not a navy policy not to allow refugees on board he 
said its a policy to render humanitarian assistance whenever 
needed and however possible in this case the commanding officer 
judged their craft to be seaworthy 
dillon said navy policy directs ships to be alert for refugees 
on the high seas and assist them as needed the policy calls for 
ships to pick up refugees if their boat is disabled or in case of 
bad weather 
filipino fishermen rescued the vietnamese off northern luzon 
island on june 27 they were taken to a refugee camp housing more 
than 4000 other vietnamese refugees on palawan island 
cooper said investigators had not determined how many people the 
refugees killed 
some said more than three were killed some said less than 
three he said 
cooper said the alleged mastermind of the cannibalism was in 
protective custody to prevent other refugees from harming him 
the manila chronicle identified the first alleged victim as a 
30yearold man named dao coung who wept and pleaded to be spared 
why not wait until i starve to death coung reportedly said 
before two men grabbed him by the feet and submerged his head in 
the sea until he was dead the paper reported 
cooper said that if the allegations against the navy crew prove 
true it would be the first time the us navy has failed to 
adequately help a group of boat people since they began fleeing 
after the fall of south vietnam to the communists in 1975 
