<TEXT>
the communist party daily 
newspaper launched an unusually strong attack wednesday on 
alexander dubcek accusing him of causing the invasion that 
destroyed the prague spring reforms of 1968 
the newspaper rude pravo charged dubcek with deceiving his 
fellow communists and the people and said he had slowed the 
implementation of reforms since 
the article was the strongest in a series of recent attacks on 
dubcek who won unprecedented national popularity for reform after 
he became party leader in january 1968 
the attacks seem designed to discredit dubcek in the eyes of his 
compatriots the former leader now a retired forestry worker in 
bratislava has received increased attention at home and abroad as 
the 20th anniversary of the august 1968 warsaw pact invasion nears 
dubcek has recently given interviews to western news media in 
which he has praised soviet leader mikhail s gorbachevs reforms 
and called for his own rehabilitation and the implementation of 
similar reforms in czechoslovakia 
the partys theoretical and political monthly nova mysl said 
in its latest issue that dubcek and his followers were responsible 
for the crisis of august 1968 when the country was on the 
brink of civil war 
during the night of aug 2021 1968 soviet and warsaw pact 
tanks moved into czechoslovakia to crush the liberal reforms 
introduced by dubcek in what came to be known as the prague spring 
rude pravo and other official media have repeatedly rejected 
parallels between dubceks reforms and those under way in the 
soviet union 
dubcek bears grave personal responsibility that the road 
to implementing reforms took much longer and was much more 
difficult the official ctk news agency quoted the rude pravo 
article as saying 
czechoslovakia is adopting some cautious economic reform in the 
wake of changes in the soviet union but has done little to reform 
either the arts or political structures 
rude pravos attack seemed to be an attempt to blame dubcek for 
the lack of more radical changes 
dubcek was no pioneer of democratic freedoms in the party and 
society the article said he became coresponsible for 
unparalleled autocratic manners and assumed the right to 
decide for the whole party at the most fateful moments it said 
thanks to his lack of reliability the leadership of the party 
lost its credibility and leaders of czechoslovakias east bloc 
allies no longer believed we would be able to handle the 
continuously deteriorating situation rude pravo said 
the czechoslovak leadership has refused to reevaluate the events 
of 1968 
gustav husak the communist leader who took over as party leader 
from dubcek in 1969 was replaced in december but there have been 
few indications the new leader milos jakes is less hardline 
jakes oversaw the purge of half a million communists after the 1968 
invasion 
