<TEXT>
coronary bypass surgery improves the survival of 
highrisk patients with heart disease and the benefits persist for 
at least 12 years a study concludes 
the research conducted in europe found that men with serious 
heart disease who got the operations outlived those who were 
treated with medicines however the difference between the two 
groups faded over time 
coronary bypass operations are often performed to relieve 
symptoms of heart pain called angina whether the surgery helps 
people live longer is controversial 
two other longrunning us studies have found no benefit of the 
common operations on survival however experts say differences in 
the health of patients who took part in the three studies probably 
explain why the european outcome was better 
that followup known as the european coronary surgery study 
group found that after five years 92 percent of the bypass 
patients were alive compared with 83 percent in a group treated 
with medicine after 12 years 71 percent of the surgical patients 
and 67 percent of the medical patients were living 
the reasons for the loss of a beneficial effect of surgery 
after five years are unknown and merit further study the doctors 
wrote 
the latest results of the european study directed by dr 
edvardas varnauskas of sahlgrenska hospital in goteborg sweden 
were published in thursdays new england journal of medicine 
the study was conducted on 767 men all under age 65 who had 
mild or moderate angina most were considered at high risk because 
of abnormal electrocardiograms and other signs of heart trouble 
last year about 230000 coronary bypass operations were 
performed at nonfederal hospitals in the united states in this 
surgery doctors use pieces of blood vessel to detour blood around 
clogged arteries in the heart 
in an editorial in the journal dr thomas killip of beth israel 
medical center in new york wrote that the studies show that 
surgical therapy improves prognosis in highrisk patients but 
the advantage over medical therapy declines with longer followup 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

