swarms of locusts have spread into central and east 
africa and there is an urgent need for money to fight the pests a 
un organization said wednesday 
the necessary funds are not coming in fast enough to help us 
contain this potentially lethal threat said lucas brader head 
of the united nations food and agriculture organizations emergency 
center for locust operations 
money is needed for insecticides equipment and other operating 
costs in part because of late payments by some of the romebased 
organizations major contributors the group said 
the united states which pays a quarter of the agencys budget 
last month paid 25 million of its overdue assessment for 1986 and 
1987 it has not yet paid its 1988 assessment of 607 million 
brader said 75 million acres of land must be treated in chad 
where large swarms have been sighted 
in sudan locusts have covered several hundred square miles and 
are moving east he said the insects were reported to be breeding 
in the eastern region of north darfur and the eastern regions of 
khartoum and kassala 
in ethiopia a dozen swarms of locusts have been seen in the 
asmara area near the red sea major control measures had to be 
adopted before the locusts swarmed south into the central ethiopian 
highland and toward the horn of africa brader said 
he estimated that 90 million to 100 million would be needed in 
sudan chad and ethiopia to prevent large harvest losses 
