<TEXT>
poultry scientists have given chickens new 
genes so they can resist avian leukosis a virus that costs egg 
producers 50 million to 100 million annually the agriculture 
department said wednesay 
the socalled transgenic chickens meaning there has been a 
transfer of genes from one organism to another were developed at 
the departments regional poultry research laboratory at east 
lansing mich 
these are the first transgenic chickens with economic 
potential said lyman b crittenden a poultry geneticist of the 
departments agricultural research service the agency that 
operates the laboratory 
avian leukosis virus cannot infect humans but it can cause 
tumors and other symptoms in chickens reducing egg production and 
quality he said 
the genetically altered chickens not only are resistant to the 
virus but pass on the characteristic to their offspring crittenden 
said 
in tests completed this year transgenic white leghorns 
descendants of the original embryos that underwent genetic 
transplants completely resisted repeated exposures to laboratory 
and field strains of the virus in tests lasting 40 weeks 
crittenden said 
the birds appear normal in growth health and reproductive 
ability the geneticist said even so several years of tests by 
poultry breeders will be required before similar transgenic 
chickens will be laying eggs for consumers 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

