<TEXT>
the senate passed legislation on wednesday 
granting 633 million to several federal programs running low on 
money a measure that was stalled for nearly a week because of an 
electionyear fight over aid to the nicaraguan contra rebels 
lawmakers approved the legislation on a voice vote without 
objection the senate now must work out a compromise bill with the 
house which passed a different version of the measure july 27 
the measure was touted as a dire emergency spending bill 
because it is supposed to provide money for programs that are in 
danger of running out of funds including programs in the 
departments of justice and agriculture the coast guard and the 
veterans administration 
supplemental spending bills such as this one often become grab 
bags for lawmakers eager to provide pet projects for their 
constituents but last falls budget summit pact between president 
reagan and congressional leaders specified that the bill should be 
limited to emergency spending 
most floor action on the bill was completed last thursday 
final passage was delayed as democrats and republicans spent 
days fruitlessly trying to work out a plan to aid the contras 
just before final passage of the spending bill the senate 
rejected a gop amendment 5739 that could have provided the 
contras with 20 million in military aid beyond what the democrats 
prefer 
the delay frustrated senate majority leader robert byrd 
dwva who complained to reporters that administration 
intransigence on the contra aid package threw a roadblock in front 
of the spending legislation 
they shouldnt hold the supplemental hostage to contra aid 
byrd said 
the bill which also allows the transfer of nearly 200 million 
among the budgets of several government agencies is for the 1988 
fiscal year which ends sept 30 
it contains 530 million in new spending and transfers for the 
veterans administration which needs the money for increased 
benefits and for a higher than expected caseload 
the bill initially contained 297 million for veterans but 
lawmakers added 233 million more on a voice vote after sen alan 
cranston dcalif chairman of the veterans affairs committee 
argued that the extra spending was required by law 
the legislation also would provide 75 million for the 
department of justice mostly to pay for the costs of last years 
uprisings by cuban detainees in federal prisons in atlanta and 
oakdale la 60 million for the coast guard to cover the costs of 
patrols and 55 million to help the agriculture department pay for 
drought programs 
