proposal to bring the contras new military aid 
i think this is a lineinthesand vote dole said it is 
a vote on whether you want to send effective military aid to the 
contras or not 
byrd urged republican support for his rival democratic proposal 
with its builtin guarantees against a filibuster as the only 
approach that has a chance of actually getting aid to the contras 
the byrd plan supported by an unusally broad democratic 
coalition of contraaid supporters and opponents provides no new 
military aid for the contras 
but it sets the terms for a possible second house and senate 
vote this fall which could release 163 million of stockpiled and 
previously authorized arms aid to the contras 
this approach keeps the options open and on a fast track 
byrd told the senate i hope my amendment will receive bipartisan 
support and send a signal to the nicaraguan government in the 
strongest possible way 
byrd had threatened to cut short a longscheduled summer recess 
and reconvene the senate immediately after next weeks republican 
national convention in new orleans if prolonged debate prevented 
action on his contraaid plan this week 
its absolutely silly to remain obstinate he said this 
amendment provides something without it the contras get nothing 
nothing 
but republicans complained that the byrd plan is unworkable and 
cannot guarantee that aid can actually be delivered to contra 
forces inside nicaragua they said that postponing the decision 
whether to rearm the contras may doom them as an effective fighting 
force against nicaraguas leftist sandinista government 
the byrd plan which was offered as an amendment to a defense 
department appropriations bill would provide 27 million in 
nonlethal humanitarian aid to the contras after current funds run 
out on oct 1 it also would provide 5 million in medical help to 
the innocent civilian victims of the war in nicaragua 
the plan also calls for accelerated votes later this year with 
a 10hour limit on debate to release the 163 million in 
previously authorized military aid if president reagan certifies 
that nicaragua has created an emergency in central america that 
threatens the existence of the contras 
it bars the central intelligence agency or the defense 
department from delivering the aid and directs the agency for 
international development aid to do the job 
doles rival plan offered as an amendment to another spending 
bill would provide the 27 million in nonlethal aid and also 
release the stockpiled arms immediately 
at one time dole also had been proposing 20 million in 
immediate military aid but revised that prior to the vote on his 
amendment to settle for immediately release of the 163 million 
stockpile 
