<DOCNO> AP880810-0311 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
japans merchandise trade surplus rose in july from 
a year earlier for the first time in 15 months the government said 
wednesday 
economists said it was too soon to conclude the steady shrinkage 
in japans surplus had come to an end and they noted that the 
surplus with the united states continued to shrink 
but some noted that japanese companies have been raising export 
prices lately something that tends to swell the surplus 
japans worldwide surplus rose 35 percent to 718 billion from 
694 billion in july 1987 and was also up sharply from the 593 
billion posted in june the finance ministry said 
japans surplus with the united states its biggest trading 
partner shrank 63 percent to 449 billion from 479 billion in 
july 1987 it was up from 363 billion in june of this year 
although the dollar has risen sharply against the japanese yen 
this year helping make japanese goods more competitively priced 
economists said that was probably a relatively small factor in the 
rise in the surplus 
it typically takes more than a year before changes in currency 
rates begin to show up in changes in the volume of goods shipped 
between nations the economists said 
i dont think you can read too much into one months data 
said mitchell held an economist for smith barney harris upham amp 
co in new york 
japanese export prices are rising partly because japans 
domestic economy is growing so strongly that it has created 
shortages of products for export said yoshihisa kitai economist 
for the long term credit bank of japan in new york 
moreover kitai said japanese exporters are beginning to push 
through price increases after having held prices down to avoid 
losing their share of foreign markets 
kyocera corp a maker of ceramic parts for electronics raised 
prices 18 percent earlier this year said thomas chesser a smith 
barney analyst he said kyocera dominates its market so much that 
it can afford to raise prices 
finance ministry officials attributed the widening of the 
surplus partly to increased sales of semiconductors chiefly to 
southeast asia where many japanese companies have shifted assembly 
of electronic products as a way of dealing with higher production 
costs at home 
exports of semiconductors during the month surged 513 percent 
over the previous years level to 111 billion it said 
in the long run once foreign operations are wellstocked the 
movement of manufacturing off shore should begin to shrink the 
surplus 
ministry officials said it was too early to tell if the july 
trade figures signaled a longterm turnaround from more than a year 
of shrinking japanese trade surpluses 
overall japanese exports during the month rose 162 percent to 
2313 billion from 199 billion while imports grew 231 percent 
to 159 billion from 130 billion the ministry said 
exports to the united states rose 40 percent from a year 
earlier to 795 billion while imports rose 214 percent to 346 
billion 
japans surplus with the european community grew from 153 
billion in july 1987 to 197 billion in july this year exports to 
the region rose 296 percent from a year earlier to 412 billion 
while imports grew 307 percent to 215 billion the ministry said 
exports to southeast asia grew 232 percent to 577 billion 
while imports from the region rose 267 percent to 405 billion 
it said 
when seasonally adjusted japans trade surplus rose to 624 
billion from 519 billion the previous month 
japan calculates its trade figures on a customsclearance basis 
which includes transportation and insurance costs in imports but 
not in exports if the costs were added to both japans trade 
surplus would be higher 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

